==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Propitiate
<hw>Pro*pi"ti*ate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.
& p. p.</pos> <conjf>Propitiated</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Propitiating</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L.
<ets>propitiatus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>propitiare</ets> to propitiate,
fr. <ets>propitius</ets> favorable. See <er>Propitious</er>.]</ety>
<def>To appease to render favorable; to make propitious; to
conciliate.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Let fierce Achilles, dreadful in his rage,⟦br⟧
The god <qex>propitiate</qex>, and the pest assuage.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Propitiate</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Propitiate
<hw>Pro*pi"ti*ate</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To make propitiation; to
atone.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

